Doc Del, Again you are an impossible class act to post after.  Your writing is beautiful, emotional, filled with pride and class.  Just wanted to tell you that.<br><br>
Hopefully the site will not fall like the fall of Saigon.  With the recent exposure in the San Francisco Examiner, and clearly our hosts &quot;connections with PBS&quot;, I am sure we is doing his best.<br><br>
April 30, 1975. I also watched it on T.V., but with a different emotional base. Really not much of one, as I recall.  I was a fresh out of Grad School with a Masters Degree and a Therapists license, ready to set the world on my couch - but instead all I could get was a job counseling junkies in a methadone center in a Hispanic Barrio.  I was the only &quot;white boy&quot; and non-addict, and I was busy learning that being a hippie was absolutely no training for working with junkies.  Strange, the clinic is still there, the war ended.<br><br>
The fall of Saigon and the loss of the &quot;bad&quot; war, and me, having then been out of my &quot;2 years of civilian service, in lieu of military service, to the good of my country&quot; by 4 years, had distanced myself from the war, and the anti-war protestors.  By then the protestors seemed to be the majority, and they didn't need &quot;firebrands&quot; as much, and I had rent to pay, and food to buy.<br><br>
